articles.text:
This Regulation lays down uniform requirements concerning the security of network and information systems supporting the business processes of financial entities as follows:

(a) requirements applicable to financial entities in relation to:
(i) information and communication technology (ICT) risk management;
(ii) reporting of major ICT-related incidents and notifying, on a voluntary basis, significant cyber threats to competent authorities;
(iii) reporting of major operational or security payment-related incidents to competent authorities;
(iv) digital operational resilience testing;
(v) information and intelligence sharing in relation to cyber threats and vulnerabilities;
(vi) measures for the sound management of ICT third-party risk;

(b) requirements in relation to the contractual arrangements between ICT third-party service providers and financial entities;

(c) rules on the establishment and conduct of the Oversight Framework for critical ICT third-party service providers when providing services to financial entities;

(d) rules on cooperation among competent authorities, and rules on supervision and enforcement by competent authorities in relation to all matters covered by this Regulation.

1. This Regulation applies to the following entities:
(a) credit institutions;
(b) payment institutions, including payment institutions exempted pursuant to Directive (EU) 2015/2366;
(c) account information service providers;
(d) electronic money institutions;
(e) investment firms;
(f) crypto-asset service providers and issuers of asset-referenced tokens;
(g) central securities depositories;
(h) central counterparties;
(i) trading venues;
(j) trade repositories;
(k) managers of alternative investment funds;
(l) management companies;
(m) data reporting service providers;
(n) insurance and reinsurance undertakings;
(o) insurance intermediaries, reinsurance intermediaries and ancillary insurance intermediaries;
(p) institutions for occupational retirement provision;
(q) credit rating agencies;
(r) administrators of critical benchmarks;
(s) crowdfunding service providers;
(t) securitisation repositories;
(u) ICT third-party service providers.

2. For the purposes of this Regulation, entities referred to in paragraph 1, points (a) to (t), are referred to as 'financial entities'.

3. This Regulation does not apply to:
(a) managers of alternative investment funds referred to in Article 3(2) of Directive 2011/61/EU;
(b) insurance and reinsurance undertakings referred to in Article 4 of Directive 2009/138/EC;
(c) institutions for occupational retirement provision which operate pension schemes which together have less than 15 members in total;
(d) natural or legal persons exempted pursuant to Articles 2 and 3 of Directive 2014/65/EU;
(e) insurance intermediaries, reinsurance intermediaries and ancillary insurance intermediaries which are microenterprises or small or medium-sized enterprises;
(f) post office giro institutions.

1. Financial entities shall establish governance and control frameworks ensuring effective ICT risk management to achieve a high level of digital operational resilience.

2. The management body shall define, approve, oversee and be responsible for implementing ICT risk management arrangements. In doing so, they shall:

(a) bear ultimate responsibility for managing ICT risk;
(b) establish policies ensuring high standards of availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality of data;
(c) set clear roles and responsibilities for ICT functions with effective governance arrangements;
(d) set and approve the digital operational resilience strategy, including ICT risk tolerance levels;
(e) approve and review ICT business continuity policy and response and recovery plans;
(f) approve and review ICT internal audit plans and material modifications;
(g) allocate appropriate budgets for digital resilience needs, including security awareness and staff training;
(h) approve and review policy on ICT third-party service provider arrangements;
(i) establish reporting channels regarding: third-party arrangements, planned material changes, impact assessments, and ICT incidents.

3. Non-microenterprises must establish a dedicated role or designate senior management to monitor third-party ICT service provider arrangements.

4. Management body members must actively keep up to date with sufficient knowledge and skills regarding ICT risk through regular training.

In order to address and manage ICT risk, financial entities shall use and maintain updated ICT systems, protocols and tools that are:

(a) appropriate to the magnitude of operations supporting the conduct of their activities, in accordance with the proportionality principle as referred to in Article 4;
(b) reliable;
(c) equipped with sufficient capacity to accurately process the data necessary for the performance of activities and the timely provision of services, and to deal with peak orders, message or transaction volumes, as needed, including where new technology is introduced;
(d) technologically resilient in order to adequately deal with additional information processing needs as required under stressed market conditions or other adverse situations.

Financial entities shall continuously monitor the performance of ICT systems and tools, identify and promptly address all differences between the expected and actual ICT capacity, and establish monitoring mechanisms to assess the quality of ICT services provided by third-party providers. The monitoring shall cover at minimum key performance indicators related to availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality, and latency of ICT services.

1. Financial entities must continuously monitor and control the security and functioning of ICT systems and minimize ICT risk impact through appropriate security tools and procedures.

2. Entities shall design, procure and implement ICT security policies, procedures, protocols and tools ensuring resilience, continuity, and availability of ICT systems, maintaining high standards for data availability, authenticity, integrity, and confidentiality.

3. ICT solutions must:
(a) ensure the security of the means of transfer of data;
(b) minimize corruption, loss, unauthorized access, and technical flaws;
(c) prevent the lack of availability, the impairment of the authenticity and integrity;
(d) protect data from management risks and human error.

4. As part of ICT risk management, entities shall:
(a) develop and document an information security policy;
(b) establish network management using appropriate techniques and automated isolation mechanisms;
(c) implement access limitation policies addressing access rights and ensure a sound administration thereof;
(d) implement strong authentication and cryptographic keys whereby data is encrypted based on approved cryptographic standards;
(e) implement documented ICT change management policies including software and firmware changes;
(f) maintain appropriate and comprehensive documented policies for patches and updates.

Network infrastructure must be instantaneously severed or segmented to minimise contagion in the event of a cyber attack. Change management requires appropriate management approval and specific protocols.

The ESAs shall, through the Joint Committee, in consultation with the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA), develop common regulatory technical standards in order to:

(a) specify further elements to be included in the ICT security policy, procedures, protocols and tools referred to in Article 9(2), with a view to ensuring the security of networks, enable adequate safeguards against intrusions and data misuse, preserve the availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality of data;

(b) develop further components of the controls of access management rights referred to in Article 9(4), point (c), and associated human resources policy specifying access rights, procedures for granting and revoking rights, monitoring of anomalous behaviour;

(c) develop further the mechanisms for the detection of anomalous activities referred to in Article 10(1) and criteria to trigger and initiate ICT-related incident response processes;

(d) specify further tests referred to in Article 25, including their scope, testing methodologies, outcomes and remediation activities;

(e) specify further any element of the ICT business continuity policy referred to in Article 11;

(f) specify further the rules on the backup systems and restoration procedures referred to in Article 12;

(g) specify further the elements of the post-incident reviews referred to in Article 13(2);

(h) specify further the elements and format of reporting under Article 19.

Financial entities shall comply with applicable regulatory technical standards developed under this Article upon their publication in the Official Journal.

1. Articles 5 to 15 shall not apply to microenterprises.

2. Microenterprises shall apply a simplified ICT risk management framework comprising:

(a) a summary of the policies and procedures addressing digital operational resilience, as required under Article 6(1);
(b) at least a policy on ICT risk tolerance;
(c) ICT business continuity plans that address continuity of critical or important functions, including backup systems;
(d) guidelines on ICT incidents categorisation;
(e) monitoring mechanisms;
(f) policies on ICT-related security documentation;
(g) policies on change and patch management;
(h) assessment of ICT third-party risk;
(i) ICT security training and awareness programme;
(j) internal audits on ICT risk.

3. Microenterprises shall also fulfil the requirements set out in Articles 17, 18, 19, 24, 25, 28, 29 and 30.

4. In the event of changes in their size or risk profile that would bring them beyond the definition of a microenterprise, the entity shall review its ICT risk management framework and update it accordingly within a reasonable timeframe.

1. Financial entities shall define, establish and implement an ICT-related incident management process to detect, manage and notify ICT-related incidents.

2. Entities must document all ICT incidents and cyber threats, establishing procedures for integrated monitoring, handling, and follow-up to identify root causes and prevent recurrence.

3. The management process requires:

(a) put in place early warning indicators;
(b) procedures to identify, track, log, categorise and classify incidents by priority, severity, and service criticality per Article 18(1);
(c) assign roles and responsibilities that need to be activated for different ICT-related incident types and scenarios;
(d) communication plans for staff, stakeholders, media pursuant to Article 14, client notification, escalation procedures, and information sharing with counterparty entities;
(e) reporting major incidents to senior management and the management body, detailing impact, response, and additional controls;
(f) establish ICT-related incident response procedures to mitigate impacts and ensure that services become operational and secure in a timely manner.

The ESAs shall, through the Joint Committee and in consultation with ENISA and the ECB, develop:

(a) common regulatory technical standards in order to:
(i) determine the content of reports for major ICT-related incidents pursuant to Article 19(1) and (4), based on the criteria set out in Article 18 and taking into account international cyber security standards and technical specifications;
(ii) determine the timeframe and the content of the notification to clients pursuant to Article 19(3);
(iii) determine the criteria applicable to financial entities for outsourcing the reporting obligation pursuant to Article 19(5);

(b) common implementing technical standards to establish the standard forms, templates and procedures for financial entities to report a major ICT-related incident.

Financial entities shall use the common templates, forms and procedures established in the implementing technical standards when making reports under Article 19.

The ESAs shall submit those draft regulatory technical standards and draft implementing technical standards to the Commission by 17 July 2024.

1. Without prejudice to the technical input, guidance or remedies and subsequent assistance that ENISA may provide in accordance with Directive (EU) 2022/2555, upon request of the financial entity the relevant competent authority shall, after receipt of the complete initial notification and of any subsequent report as referred to in Article 19(4), provide in a timely manner appropriate feedback or guidance to the financial entity, in particular regarding any remedies available at national level, confidential technical feedback, an overview of the cyber threats relevant to the financial entity and its sector, and guidance on the further conduct of incident response.

2. Financial entities should, where appropriate, following the receipt of supervisory feedback:
(a) update the relevant competent authority with their progress on the measures being taken;
(b) take into account the guidance when investigating the incident;
(c) integrate the guidance into their future incident response procedures.

1. Financial entities shall only use testers for the carrying out of TLPT that:

(a) are of the highest suitability and repute;
(b) possess technical and organisational capabilities and demonstrate specific expertise in threat intelligence, penetration testing and red team operations;
(c) are certified by an accreditation body in a Member State or adhere to formal codes of conduct or ethical frameworks;
(d) provide an independent assurance, or are audited, in relation to the sound management of risks associated with the carrying out of TLPT;
(e) are duly covered by relevant professional indemnity insurances, including against risks of misconduct and negligence.

2. When using internal testers, financial entities shall ensure that:
(a) such use has been approved by the relevant competent authority;
(b) the relevant competent authority has verified that the financial entity has sufficient dedicated resources and ensured that conflicts of interest are avoided throughout the design and execution phases of the test;
(c) the threat intelligence provider is external to the financial entity.

3. Financial entities shall ensure that testers contracted to conduct TLPT comply, throughout the duration of the TLPT, with the requirements set out in paragraph 1. Financial entities shall perform appropriate due diligence when selecting testers.

4. TLPT carried out in accordance with this Article and with the TIBER-EU framework as implemented in national law or as applied by the competent authorities shall be mutually recognised across Member States.

1. Financial entities shall manage ICT third-party risk as an integral component of ICT risk within their ICT risk management framework, in accordance with the following principles:

(a) financial entities that have in place contractual arrangements for the use of ICT services to run their business operations shall, at all times, remain fully responsible for compliance with, and the discharge of, all obligations under this Regulation and applicable financial services law;
(b) financial entities' management of ICT third-party risk shall be implemented in light of the principle of proportionality, taking into account:
(i) the nature, scale, complexity and importance of ICT-related dependencies;
(ii) the risks arising from contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services.

2. Entities shall adopt and regularly review a strategy on ICT third-party risk including policies on use of ICT services supporting critical or important functions, applied individually and on sub-consolidated and consolidated bases.

3. Financial entities shall maintain and update at entity level, and at sub-consolidated and consolidated levels, a register of information in relation to all contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services provided by ICT third-party service providers. The register shall be reported yearly to competent authorities.

4. Before entering into a contractual arrangement on the use of ICT services, financial entities shall:
(a) assess whether the contractual arrangement covers the use of ICT services supporting a critical or important function;
(b) assess whether supervisory conditions for contracting are met;
(c) identify and assess all relevant risks in relation to the contractual arrangement, including concentration risk;
(d) undertake all due diligence on prospective ICT third-party service providers;
(e) identify and assess conflicts of interest that the contractual arrangement may cause.

5. ICT third-party service providers shall comply with appropriate information security standards. Where contractual arrangements concern critical or important functions, financial entities shall, before concluding the arrangements, duly consider the use of the most up-to-date and highest quality information security standards.

6. In exercising access and audit rights on ICT third-party service providers, financial entities shall determine the frequency of audits and inspections based on a risk-based approach and commonly accepted audit standards.

7. Financial entities shall have the right to terminate contractual arrangements where:
(a) significant breach of applicable laws, regulations or contractual terms;
(b) circumstances altering the performance of the functions under the contractual arrangement;
(c) evidence of weaknesses in the ICT third-party service provider's overall ICT risk management;
(d) circumstances where the competent authority can no longer effectively supervise the financial entity.

8. For critical or important functions, financial entities shall put in place exit strategies for orderly termination of the contractual arrangement.

1. The rights and obligations of the financial entity and of the ICT third-party service provider shall be clearly allocated and set out in writing. The full contract shall include the service level agreement and be documented in one written document that is available to the parties on paper, or in a document with another downloadable, durable and accessible format.

2. Contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services shall include at least the following elements:

(a) a clear and complete description of all functions and ICT services to be provided by the ICT third-party service provider, indicating whether subcontracting of an ICT service supporting a critical or important function, or material parts thereof, is permitted, and, where it is, the conditions applicable to such subcontracting;
(b) the locations, namely the regions or countries, where the contracted or subcontracted functions and ICT services are to be provided and where data is to be processed, including the storage location, and the requirement for the ICT third-party service provider to notify the financial entity if it envisages changing such locations;
(c) provisions on availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality in relation to the protection of data, including personal data;
(d) provisions on ensuring access to, recovery and return of, in an easily accessible format, personal and non-personal data processed by the ICT third-party service provider in the event of the insolvency, resolution or discontinuation of the business operations of that provider, or in the event of the termination of the contractual arrangements;
(e) service level descriptions, including updates and revisions thereof;
(f) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to provide assistance to the financial entity at no additional cost, or at a cost that is determined ex-ante, when an ICT incident that is related to the ICT service provided to the financial entity occurs;
(g) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to fully cooperate with the competent authorities and the resolution authorities of the financial entity, including persons appointed by them;
(h) termination rights and related minimum notice periods for the termination of the contractual arrangements, in accordance with the expectations of competent authorities and resolution authorities;
(i) conditions for the participation of ICT third-party service providers in the financial entities' ICT security awareness programmes and digital operational resilience training.

3. For contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services supporting critical or important functions, the following elements shall additionally be included:

(a) full service level descriptions, including updates and revisions thereof, with precise quantitative and qualitative performance targets within the agreed service levels;
(b) notice periods and reporting obligations of the ICT third-party service provider to the financial entity, including notification of any development that might have a material impact on the ICT third-party service provider's ability to effectively provide the ICT services;
(c) requirements for the ICT third-party service provider to implement and test business contingency plans;
(d) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to participate in and fully cooperate with the financial entity's TLPT as referred to in Articles 26 and 27;
(e) the right to monitor, on an ongoing basis, the ICT third-party service provider's performance, which shall entail:
(i) unrestricted rights of access, inspection and audit by the financial entity, or an appointed third party, and by the competent authority;
(ii) the right to agree on alternative assurance levels if other clients' rights are affected;
(f) exit strategies, in particular the establishment of a mandatory adequate transition period:
(i) during which the ICT third-party service provider will continue providing the respective functions or ICT services with a view to reducing the risk of disruption at the financial entity or to allowing the financial entity to effectively transition to another third-party service provider or to in-house solutions;
(ii) allowing the financial entity to migrate to another ICT third-party service provider or to in-house solutions.

4. Financial entities and ICT third-party service providers shall use standard contractual clauses developed by public authorities for specific services.

5. The ESAs shall develop draft regulatory technical standards on standard contractual clauses by 17 July 2024.

1. The Lead Overseer shall carry out the following tasks:

(a) be the primary point of contact for the critical ICT third-party service provider in relation to the exercise of the oversight mandate;
(b) on the basis of a recommendation from the Oversight Forum, take measures;
(c) draw up the individual oversight plan describing the annual supervisory objectives and the main oversight actions planned for each critical ICT third-party service provider;
(d) jointly conduct, with the relevant competent authorities, all activities and tasks with respect to the performance of their oversight mandate.

2. The Lead Overseer shall carry out, in relation to critical ICT third-party service providers subject to its oversight, the following tasks:

(a) carry out general investigations and inspections;
(b) request information and documentation from the critical ICT third-party service provider;
(c) require the critical ICT third-party service provider to participate in general investigations and inspections;
(d) impose non-financial penalties in accordance with Article 35(6);
(e) issue recommendations to the critical ICT third-party service provider;
(f) draw up the annual oversight report.

3. Financial entities shall support the Lead Overseer in its supervision of critical ICT third-party service providers and ensure that their contractual arrangements with such providers allow the Lead Overseer to exercise its oversight mandate effectively.

1. The Lead Overseer may, by simple request or by decision, require critical ICT third-party service providers to provide all information that is necessary for the Lead Overseer to carry out its duties under this Regulation, including all relevant business or operational documents, contracts, policies, documentation, ICT security audit reports, ICT-related incident reports, as well as any information relating to parties to whom the critical ICT third-party service provider has outsourced operational functions or activities.

2. When sending a simple request for information under paragraph 1, the Lead Overseer shall:
(a) refer to this Article as the legal basis of the request;
(b) state the purpose of the request;
(c) specify what information is required;
(d) set a time limit within which the information is to be provided;
(e) indicate that there is no obligation to provide the information, but that a voluntary reply to the request must not be incorrect or misleading.

3. Financial entities that use services from the critical ICT third-party service provider may be required to assist in providing information where the Lead Overseer determines this is necessary and where information is held at the level of the financial entity.

4. Financial entities shall maintain comprehensive records of their contractual arrangements with critical ICT third-party service providers to facilitate responses to information requests from the Lead Overseer.

1. In order to carry out its duties under this Regulation, and with the assistance of the competent authorities of the Member States in which the critical ICT third-party service provider operates or in which the relevant premises are located, the Lead Overseer may conduct investigations of critical ICT third-party service providers.

2. The Lead Overseer shall have the power to:
(a) examine records, data, procedures, and any other material relevant to the execution of its tasks, irrespective of the medium on which they are stored;
(b) take or obtain certified copies of or extracts from such records, data, procedures and other material;
(c) summon and ask representatives of the critical ICT third-party service provider for oral or written explanations on facts or documents relating to the subject-matter and purpose of the inspection and to record the answers;
(d) interview any other natural or legal person who consents to be interviewed for the purpose of collecting information relating to the subject-matter of an investigation.

3. Financial entities may be interviewed or requested to provide supporting documentation or evidence during a Lead Overseer investigation of a critical ICT third-party service provider.

4. Financial entities shall cooperate fully and promptly with Lead Overseer investigations and shall ensure that their contractual arrangements with critical ICT third-party service providers include provisions facilitating such cooperation.

1. In order to carry out its duties under this Regulation, the Lead Overseer may, with prior notification, conduct on-site inspections at any business premises, land or property of the critical ICT third-party service provider, as well as off-site inspections.

2. The Lead Overseer shall have the power to:
(a) enter any business premises, land or property;
(b) examine the books, records and data in whatever form they are stored;
(c) obtain or take copies of documents;
(d) carry out audits of the ICT risk management, policies, procedures, ICT systems and processes of the critical ICT third-party service provider;
(e) interview staff.

3. Officials and other persons authorised by the Lead Overseer to conduct an on-site inspection shall exercise their powers upon production of a written authorisation.

4. Officials authorised by the Lead Overseer may also seal any business premises and books and records for the period of, and to the extent necessary for, the inspection.

5. Financial entities shall be notified of and may be required to participate in or facilitate Lead Overseer inspections of critical ICT third-party service providers where those inspections relate to services provided to the financial entity.

6. Financial entities shall ensure that contractual arrangements with critical ICT third-party service providers include provisions allowing Lead Overseer and competent authority inspection access.

1. The Lead Overseer shall draw up an individual oversight plan for each critical ICT third-party service provider covering:

(a) the annual supervisory objectives for the critical ICT third-party service provider, taking into account the ICT third-party service provider's risk profile;
(b) the key actions planned during the oversight cycle, including the general investigations and on-site inspections planned;
(c) any other task the Lead Overseer deems appropriate.

2. Following the completion of oversight activities, the Lead Overseer shall issue recommendations to the critical ICT third-party service provider to be complied with within the period specified. Those recommendations shall address:
(a) technical measures and organisational measures;
(b) ICT security measures.

3. Where the critical ICT third-party service provider does not comply with the recommendations within the specified period, the Lead Overseer shall notify the competent authorities of the financial entities using the services of that provider.

4. Financial entities shall adapt their use of and reliance on critical ICT third-party service providers based on the outcomes of Lead Overseer oversight activities and recommendations.

5. Financial entities shall monitor competent authority communications regarding the compliance status of their critical ICT third-party service providers.

The ESAs shall develop, through the Joint Committee, draft regulatory technical standards to specify:

(a) the information to be provided by ICT third-party service providers in the application for voluntary designation as referred to in Article 31;
(b) the content, structure and format of the information to be submitted, disclosed or reported by critical ICT third-party service providers pursuant to Article 35(1), point (c), and Article 39;
(c) the criteria for determining the composition of the joint examination team and the modalities for the coordination between the Lead Overseer and the competent authorities in relation to oversight activities, exchanges of information and co-operation tasks;
(d) the details of competent authorities' cooperation with the Lead Overseer, in particular the type of information to be exchanged;
(e) the modalities of how financial entities can facilitate exchanges of information to the Lead Overseer during oversight activities.

Financial entities shall comply with applicable regulatory technical standards developed under this Article, which specify how to facilitate oversight information exchanges between financial entities and Lead Overseers.

1. Financial entities may exchange amongst themselves cyber threat information and intelligence, including indicators of compromise, tactics, techniques and procedures, cyber security alerts and configuration tools, to the extent that such information and intelligence sharing:

(a) aims to enhance the digital operational resilience of financial entities, in particular through awareness-raising in relation to cyber threats, limiting or impeding the cyber threats' ability to spread, supporting defence capabilities, threat detection techniques, mitigation strategies or response and recovery stages;
(b) takes place within trusted communities of financial entities;
(c) is implemented through information-sharing arrangements that protect the potentially sensitive nature of the information shared and is governed by rules of conduct in full respect of business confidentiality, protection of personal data in accordance with Regulation (EU) 2016/679, and guidelines on competition policy.

2. For the purpose of paragraph 1, financial entities shall designate a member of senior management responsible for the implementation and overseeing of the information-sharing arrangements and for reporting to the management body on relevant developments.

3. The information sharing arrangements referred to in paragraph 1 may include, where permissible:
(a) membership of information-sharing communities;
(b) sharing of information including indicators of compromise, tactics, techniques and procedures;
(c) analysis of information;
(d) threat intelligence.

4. Competent authorities shall be informed of participation in information-sharing arrangements and may request information about the arrangements. Financial entities shall cooperate with competent authorities on matters related to information-sharing arrangements.

1. Competent authorities shall have all supervisory and investigatory powers necessary to fulfil their duties under this Regulation. These include:

(a) access to any document, data, procedure or any other material in any format, wherever stored;
(b) on-site inspections or investigations at any business premises, land or property;
(c) requests for explanations from management body members and staff;
(d) interim measures in accordance with national law where there is immediate and significant risk to financial stability;
(e) temporary bans on any person from exercising managerial responsibilities;
(f) requirements to adopt measures to bring conduct into conformity with this Regulation, and to cease conduct that is in breach of this Regulation.

2. Without prejudice to the right to provide explanations, financial entities shall cooperate with competent authority investigations, on-site inspections and information requests. Obstruction of supervisory activities is a breach of this Regulation.

3. Financial entities must implement remedial measures within the timeframes specified by the competent authority.

1. Without prejudice to the right of competent authorities to impose supervisory measures, Member States shall lay down rules on administrative penalties and other administrative measures applicable to breaches of this Regulation and shall take all measures necessary to ensure that they are implemented.

2. Administrative penalties for financial entities that are legal persons shall not exceed:
(a) EUR 10,000,000 or, if higher, 2% of the total annual worldwide turnover according to the latest available accounts for breaches of the ICT risk management, incident reporting, resilience testing, and third-party risk management requirements;
(b) EUR 5,000,000 for natural persons.

3. When determining the appropriate administrative penalty, competent authorities shall take into account all relevant circumstances, including:
(a) the gravity and the duration of the breach;
(b) the degree of responsibility of the natural or legal person;
(c) the financial strength of the natural or legal person responsible;
(d) the importance of profits gained or losses avoided;
(e) the losses incurred by third parties as a result of the breach;
(f) the level of cooperation with the competent authority;
(g) previous breaches;
(h) any remedial measures adopted.

4. Competent authorities may publish administrative penalties imposed.
